<h2>Day 2 (March 7): The Correction — F&G Hits 12</h2>

<p>By the morning of March 7, BTC had dropped to <strong>$67,908</strong> — a decline of 3.71% from the Day 1 close. The Fear &amp; Greed Index, rather than recovering, fell further to <strong>12</strong>. That's the deepest extreme fear reading since the competition began.</p>

<p>The market context tells a coherent story:</p>

<ul style="margin: 16px 0 16px 24px; line-height: 1.9;">
    <li>Three consecutive days of declining volume: $113.9B → $90.75B → lower</li>
    <li>BTC dominance declining: 56.58% (from 57.23% peak) — early signal of alt-rotation brewing</li>
    <li>Gold tokens outperforming (+1.7%) — flight to safety within crypto, classic capitulation signal</li>
    <li>HYPE (Hyperliquid) up +0.73% on a day when most assets fell 3–4% — the derivatives market is exhibiting structural divergence</li>
</ul>

<p>This is not a random correction. The volume decline combined with sentiment deterioration suggests that the BTC rally from $63.8K was largely mechanical (deleveraging, liquidation cascades clearing) rather than fundamentally driven by fresh buying. V3.6's accumulation thesis — that extreme fear eventually mean-reverts — is structurally intact but will require more patience than the initial 48-hour window suggested.</p>

<h3>What the Correction Means for Each Bot</h3>

<p><strong>V3.5 Grid:</strong> The 6 open positions (entries at $67K–$73K) are now slightly underwater at $67,908. However, this does not erode the <strong>+$921.86 in confirmed realized profits</strong> — those closed trades are locked in. What the correction does is create new grid entries at lower levels. If BTC oscillates around $67K–$69K, V3.5 will continue printing trades.</p>

<p>The deeper the correction, the wider the potential grid range. V3.5's design boundary is $56,900–$67,200. With BTC pushing back toward that lower bound, the grid may become even more productive than it was at $71K–$73K (where it was operating above its designed optimal range).</p>

<p><strong>V3.6 Fear &amp; Greed:</strong> The 10 open positions are accumulating into a deepening fear environment. This is uncomfortable but mechanically correct. The V3.6 thesis doesn't require perfect entry timing — it requires sentiment to eventually normalize. With F&amp;G at 12, the mean-reversion distance from neutral (50) is now <em>larger</em> than when the competition launched. Larger mean-reversion distance = larger potential gain when recovery begins.</p>

<p>The risk is continued decline. If BTC drops to $60K with F&amp;G at 5, V3.6's accumulation positions will be substantially underwater. That's the strategy's core risk — it bets on mean-reversion happening before a sustained bear market begins.</p>

<h2>The Strategy Divergence: 40 Hours In</h2>

<p>After 40 hours of competition, the strategic picture is unusually clear.</p>

<h3>V3.5: The Grid Bot Outperformed Its Own Thesis</h3>

<p>V3.5 was designed with a target range of <strong>$56,900–$67,200</strong>. During this competition period, BTC spent most of the time <em>above</em> that range ($68K–$73K). A grid bot operating above its designed range is sub-optimal — it has fewer grid levels to work with, positions are more concentrated at the top of the range.</p>

<p>Yet V3.5 still generated 410 trades and +$921.86 in realized profit. In 40 hours.</p>

<p>The lesson here isn't "grids work perfectly at any price." It's more nuanced: <strong>grid bots don't need precise range prediction — they need price oscillation</strong>. BTC oscillating between $68K and $73K gave V3.5 ~$5,000 worth of range to work in. The grid captured most of it. The fact that this range was above the "designed" range slightly reduced efficiency but didn't prevent the strategy from printing.</p>

<h3>V3.6: The Setup Is Getting Better, Not Worse</h3>

<p>V3.6's zero realized P&amp;L will look like underperformance. Compared to V3.5's +$921.86, it obviously is — at this moment in time.</p>

<p>But the correct comparison isn't V3.6 Week 4 Day 2.5 vs V3.5 Week 4 Day 2.5. It's V3.6 at the end of the competition vs V3.5 at the end of the competition. The academic framework V3.6 was built on (Zhang &amp; Watts 2025; Farzulla 2026) shows F&amp;G mean-reversion strategies produce their best returns over 3–8 week horizons, not 48-hour windows.</p>

<p>Here's the key data point: V3.6 launched with F&amp;G=22 and is now accumulating at F&amp;G=12. The bot entered at what it thought was extreme fear. The market responded by becoming <em>more</em> fearful. Every additional fear unit below 22 makes the eventual mean-reversion recovery larger. V3.6 is not losing. It's loading.</p>

