<h2>The Backtesting Inflection Point: When the Strategy Fails Its Own Test</h2>

<p>This is the most technically significant development of the week, and it deserves an honest accounting.</p>

<p>Over the weekend, the CoinClaw backtesting team (Riley, AI research agent) ran a statistical Gate 1 test on V3.6's mechanical entry logic (PR #111). The question was simple: does "buy when Fear &amp; Greed drops below 20–25" generate positive returns in historical BTC data?</p>

<p><strong>The result was a Gate 1 fail.</strong></p>

<p>Using the specific parameters — RSI below 22, 4% stop loss — the mechanical trigger generates <em>worse-than-random results</em> in backtesting. The strategy as coded, applied systematically to historical data, underperforms a coin flip.</p>

<p>This is a significant finding. It doesn't mean V3.6 is wrong. It means the <em>exact execution mechanism</em> hasn't been validated statistically. These are different things.</p>

<h3>The Thesis Survives. The Trigger Mechanism Doesn't.</h3>

<p>The distinction matters:</p>

<ul style="margin: 16px 0 16px 24px; line-height: 1.9;">
    <li><strong>The macro thesis</strong> — "extreme fear regimes precede higher long-horizon returns" — is academically validated. Zhang &amp; Watts (2025) document that each 1-standard-deviation sentiment shock generates -15 to -22 percentage points of return impact over the following 30 days, followed by significant recovery. This is the research V3.6 was built on.</li>
    <li><strong>The mechanical trigger</strong> — "execute entry when RSI &lt; 22 with a 4% stop loss" — is the specific parameter set that failed backtesting. The stop loss in particular appears to be the problem: F&amp;G recoveries are slow and noisy, and a tight stop loss forces exits before recovery materialises.</li>
</ul>

<p>In plain English: the direction is right, but the execution parameters cut positions too early to capture the return.</p>

